#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:674
msgid "What can this plugin do and how does it work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:679
msgid "This plugin is privacy-oriented: optimization runs on your server and does not require sending your site data to third-party services."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:681
msgid "WP Optimizer is modular, so you can enable only the features you need to keep the plugin overhead low."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:683
msgid "Server enhancements such as compression, browser caching, and server rules."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:684
msgid "Caching layers for queries, database results, objects, and static pages."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:685
msgid "Minification for HTML, CSS, and JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:686
msgid "Local image optimization and conversion workflows."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:687
msgid "Database cleanup, optimization, and backups."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:688
msgid "Security hardening and WordPress behavior toggles."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:689
msgid "Update controls, diagnostics, logs, and admin utilities."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:691
msgid ""
"Because modules can affect different parts of WordPress, the safest approach is to enable one feature at a time and test the front end after each change."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:698
msgid "What should I enable first on a live site?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:702
msgid "Start with lower-risk optimizations, then move to the more aggressive ones only after testing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:704
#, php-format
msgid "Begin with <a href=\"%s\">browser cache and compression settings</a> because they usually improve delivery without changing page logic."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:705
#, php-format
msgid "Configure <a href=\"%s\">media optimization</a> for new uploads before launching large bulk jobs."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:706
#, php-format
msgid "Create a <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before cleanup tasks or bigger tuning sessions."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:707
#, php-format
msgid "Add <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> last, enabling one option at a time and verifying the front end after each step."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:715
msgid "Where can I configure optimization parameters?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:719
#, php-format
msgid "Most optimization options are configurable in the <a href=\"%s\">Modules Options panel</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:720
#, php-format
msgid "Global tasks such as cron, module activation, telemetry, reset, export, and restore are available from the <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:727
msgid "Can cache or minify break my layout?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:731
msgid ""
"Yes. Aggressive caching and front-end minification can expose conflicts in themes or plugins that rely on specific asset order, inline scripts, or dynamic "
"output."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:733
#, php-format
msgid "Enable <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> gradually: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript do not need to be turned on all at once."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:734
#, php-format
msgid "After each change, clear or reset <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and test important pages while logged out as well."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:735
msgid "If something breaks, disable the last option you enabled first. That is usually the fastest way to isolate the conflict."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:743
msgid "How does the media optimizer work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:747
msgid "Media optimizer works in three different ways:"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:749
#, php-format
msgid "By a scheduled event it's able to collect and optimize any media uploaded daily. <a href='%s'>Here</a> you can configure all schedule related settings."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:750
msgid "By a specific path scanner, Media optimizer will run a background activity to optimize all images present in the input path."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:751
msgid ""
"By a whole database scanner, Media optimizer will run a background activity to check all images saved in your WordPress library optimizing each image and "
"every thumbnail associated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:753
#, php-format
msgid "Any image optimization will be run following your settings set <a href=\"%s\">Here</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:760
msgid "Why are image optimization jobs not starting?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:764
msgid "Bulk image optimization runs in background, so it depends on the plugin scheduler and on image libraries available on the server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:766
#, php-format
msgid "Verify that <a href=\"%s\">cron is active</a>; background jobs will not progress if scheduled tasks are not running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:767
msgid "Check that Imagick or GD is available in PHP. Imagick gives the best coverage, but GD can still handle basic processing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:768
#, php-format
msgid "Review your <a href=\"%s\">media settings</a> before starting a full-library scan so the job uses the correct quality and format options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:776
msgid "Do I need Redis or Memcached for object cache?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:780
msgid "Only the object cache feature requires Redis or Memcached. The other optimization modules can still be used without them."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:782
#, php-format
msgid "If your server does not provide Redis or Memcached, leave <a href=\"%s\">object cache</a> disabled."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:783
msgid "Static page cache, database/query cache, browser cache, compression, and minify do not depend on an external object cache server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:791
msgid "How can I clean the database safely?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:795
msgid "Database cleanup is most useful when you do it conservatively and with a rollback path ready."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:797
#, php-format
msgid "Create a fresh <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before deleting revisions, transients, orphaned data, or other leftovers."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:798
#, php-format
msgid "Run cleanup tasks from the <a href=\"%s\">Database module</a> when the site is stable and no import, migration, or major update is running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:799
msgid "If the result is not what you expected, restore the backup first instead of guessing which rows changed."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:807
msgid "Can I export settings before major changes?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:811
#, php-format
msgid "Yes. The <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a> lets you export, import, reset, or restore plugin options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:812
msgid "Use an export before testing aggressive cache, minify, or security changes so you can quickly return to a known-good configuration."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:819
msgid "Does WP Optimizer work on multisite?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:823
msgid "Yes. The plugin supports multisite and can be network-activated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:824
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Even on multisite, test optimization changes gradually from the <a href=\"%s\">module settings</a> because each subsite may use different themes, plugins, "
"and traffic patterns."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:861
msgid "Is WP Optimizer compatible with WP Rocket, FlyingPress, Perfmatters, LiteSpeed Cache and other optimization plugins?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:863
msgid "WP Optimizer can coexist with other optimization plugins, but the same optimization layer should not be enabled in more than one plugin."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:864
msgid ""
"Choose a single owner for page cache, minification, asset combination, and server rules. Then clear every cache and test the site after changing the "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:869
msgid "Will WP Optimizer speed up my WooCommerce store?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:871
msgid ""
"It can improve cacheable storefront pages, assets, images, and database work, but the result depends on the store, hosting, theme, extensions, and traffic."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:872
msgid ""
"Cart, checkout, and account routes are excluded from page caching and runtime HTML optimization automatically. Test product, cart, checkout, account, "
"payment, and multilingual flows before using aggressive settings."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:877
msgid "How do I exclude a page from caching?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:879
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Open the <a href=\"%s\">Static Pages Cache configuration</a> and add an exclude rule for the required path or URL pattern. WooCommerce cart, checkout, and "
"account routes are excluded automatically."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:884
msgid "Does WP Optimizer minify and combine CSS and JavaScript?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:886
#, php-format
msgid "Yes. The <a href=\"%s\">Minify module</a> can minify HTML, CSS, and JavaScript and can optionally try to combine CSS or JavaScript files."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:887
msgid "Enable each option separately, clear cache, and verify important pages after every change because themes and plugins may depend on asset order."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:892
msgid "Do I need a CDN to use WP Optimizer?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:894
msgid "No. Caching, minification, media optimization, and server features run without a CDN."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:895
msgid "You can still use a CDN independently. If it caches HTML, coordinate its purge behavior with WP Optimizer so visitors do not receive stale pages."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:900
msgid "Will WP Optimizer slow down my wp-admin dashboard?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:902
msgid "Front-end transformations do not normally run on wp-admin pages, and cache layers can be configured to skip administrative requests."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:903
msgid ""
"Monitoring, backups, and bulk media or database jobs still use server resources. Schedule heavy work outside busy periods and disable modules you do not "
"need."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:908
msgid "Can I use WP Optimizer with Cloudflare?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:910
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Yes. The <a href=\"%s\">Cloudflare module</a> can purge the Cloudflare edge cache when WP Optimizer cache is cleared, using a scoped API token and Zone ID."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:911
msgid "Avoid duplicating HTML caching or optimization features without testing, and verify that both cache layers are purged after content changes."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:916
msgid "What happens to my cache when I edit a post or product?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:918
msgid ""
"When automatic purge is enabled, WordPress content-change hooks invalidate affected static-page and query cache entries after posts, products, terms, or "
"comments change."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:919
msgid "WooCommerce-sensitive routes remain excluded. If the Cloudflare integration is enabled, WP Optimizer also requests the configured edge-cache purge."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:924
msgid "How do I completely uninstall WP Optimizer and remove its data?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:926
#, php-format
msgid ""
"For the cleanest removal, first use the <a href=\"%s\">module reset tools</a> so active modules can remove managed drop-ins, generated storage, and local "
"server rules. Then deactivate and delete WP Optimizer from the WordPress Plugins screen."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:927
msgid ""
"The uninstall routine removes plugin options, scheduled media hooks, and plugin database tables from every site in a Multisite network. Shared WPS framework "
"data is removed only when no other installed component uses it."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:932
msgid "Is there a developer API for clearing the cache?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:934
msgid "Yes. Integration code can guard with function_exists() and call wpopt_flush_cache() to flush active WP Optimizer cache layers."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:935
msgid ""
"Bulk processes can use wpopt_suspend_cache_auto_purge() and wpopt_resume_cache_auto_purge() to avoid repeated purges. The supported functions and examples "
"are documented in EXTERNAL-API.md."
msgstr ""

